  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency food assistance and bread value chain rehabilitation targeting the underserved and food insecure communities of Hama, Homs and Quneitra</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project is implemented in the Hama, Homs and Quneitra governorates. Whilst food needs are widespread across Syria, in terms of severity, both Hama and Quneitra are amongst the top three governorates presenting the highest levels of food insecurity at 66 and 58 percent, respectively. Hama&#x2019;s high food insecurity rate is heavily impacted by the worsening agricultural situation whereby the ongoing drought and associated reduction in agricultural output has translated into high unemployment rates and reduced purchasing power amongst the predominantly agrarian community. Quneitra on the other hand, whilst experiencing similar employment challenges and its associated disruption to local food systems and food availability. In terms of Homs, the governorate has a food insecurity prevalence rate of 51 percent.  

WFP proposes an integrated approach to address basic food needs at a community level: across the underserved areas of Hama, Homs and Quneitra, through a combination of immediate crisis response interventions such as in-kind and cash assistance to vulnerable families, as well as early recovery initiatives aimed at restoring specifically food systems related to the bread value chain.

This FSA project directly targets 203,500 affected people.</narrative>
  </description>
